article.description: Iciss Tillis scored a career-high 30 points as No. 1 Duke cruised to an 81-63 victory over Florida State in an Atlantic Coast Conference matchup.
article.headline: Tillis scores career-high 30 points for Duke
article.linkText: Surprising source helps top-ranked Duke stay unbeaten
article.story:
DURHAM, N. C. (AP) -- With All-American Alana Beard in foul
trouble, Iciss Tillis made sure No. 1 Duke stayed unbeaten.

	   Tillis scored a career-high 30 points, 17 in the second half, as
the Blue Devils used a late run to beat Florida State 81-63 on Sunday.

	   Beard picked up her fourth foul with 12:16 left and sat out the
rest of the game. She was held to a season-low seven points, ending
her streak of scoring in double figures at 40 games.

	   "We did our job on Beard, and then Tillis did her job on us,''
Florida State coach Sue Semrau said.

	   Michele Matyasovsky added 12 points for Duke (19-0, 7-0 Atlantic
Coast Conference), which led 37-32 lead at halftime before fending
off the Seminoles in the second half.

	   Tillis made 12 of 21 shots, hit all five of her free-throw
attempts, and finished with a team-high eight rebounds.

	   "We may have been too up for this game,'' Tillis said. "We
might have come out with a little too much energy at the start. We
were really emotional about the game.''

	   The Seminoles were the last ACC team to win at Duke, taking a
71-69 decision on Feb. 8, 2001. The Blue Devils have won 31
straight league games since.

	   Tasheika Morris scored 11 of Florida State's first 14 points in
the second half and finished with 16. Linnea Liljestrand added 10
in a reserve role for Florida State (13-5, 5-2).

	   After Beard was whistled for a charge for her fourth foul,
Florida State went on a 9-2 run to tie the game at 52. Morris
started the run with a 3-pointer, and LaQuinta Neely tied it on a
layup with 10:12 left.

	   Duke answered with the decisive 12-2 run to lock up its 21st
straight win at home. Jessica Foley scored all seven of her points
in a 2:33 span during the spurt.

	   "I was really proud of the poise and character we showed after
Alana got her fourth foul,'' Duke coach Gail Goestenkors said.
"There was a big momentum swing there.''

	   Tillis made seven of her last nine shots and scored 11 points
during a 10-minute span in the second half.

	   "I kind of knew I could take over,'' Tillis said. "I knew I
could go over the top of their post players.''

	   Duke has a chance Wednesday at North Carolina State to match
Virginia's 20-0 record in the 1985-86 season, the best start ever
by an ACC women's team.
